The paper focuses on developing a natural language instruction grounding framework for robots to execute complex instructions in dynamic environments. This involves formal synthesis and interaction with the user to identify necessary environment assumptions for successful task completion. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.RO (Robotics). The paper also involves the use of artificial intelligence techniques for natural language processing and decision-making, which suggests the sub-category cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also likely. Additionally, the paper involves the use of natural language questions and interaction with the user, which suggests the sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language) is also relevant. The paper also involves the use of formal synthesis and system control, which suggests the sub-category cs.SY (Systems and Control) is also relevant. Finally, the paper involves human-robot interaction and user-centered design, which suggests the sub-category cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) is also relevant.
